<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `opened_date` DateTime field on the `x_[scope]_case` custom
    table inside the scoped application `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field        Type        Constraints
        opened_date  DateTime    Auto-set on creation

    Per AAP Section 0.7.4 (Other User-Provided Rules):
        "Portal lookup output filtering: the lookup page returns ONLY status,
         subject, opened_date - no internal fields exposed."
    `opened_date` is therefore one of EXACTLY THREE columns whitelisted by
    the portal status-lookup endpoint for return to anonymous callers
    (../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml).

    This dictionary entry ONLY declares that the `opened_date` field exists on
    the parent table. The auto-population logic (`opened_date =
    gs.nowDateTime()` on insert if not already set) is configured by a
    separate before-insert business rule in
    ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml. The "if not already set"
    semantic is critical: synthetic seed data in
    ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml pre-populates `opened_date`
    with timestamps spanning the past 30 days so the Manager View dashboard's
    "Cases opened (30 days)" single-score widget displays a non-zero count
    on a fresh PDI immediately after Update Set commit; the business rule
    must NOT overwrite those explicit values.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 157-159:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_created", nullable = false,
                    insertable = true, updatable = false)
            @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP)
            private Date created;
        ArkCase's `created` was a JPA Date column on the `acm_case_file`
        entity, mapped to the physical column `cm_case_created`, populated
        once at insert time (`insertable=true, updatable=false`),
        forbidden from being NULL (`nullable=false`), and stored as a
        full TIMESTAMP (date + time, millisecond precision). The
        ServiceNow target captures these four JPA semantics in the
        following dictionary attributes:
          * @Temporal(TemporalType.TIMESTAMP) -> internal_type=glide_date_time
            (DateTime, NOT glide_date - AAP Section 0.5.7 explicitly
            specifies DateTime, not Date)
          * insertable=true, updatable=false -> read_only=true at the
            dictionary level (no user, agent, or manager may modify the
            value once written) plus the auto-set business rule that
            populates it on insert
          * nullable=false -> the auto-set business rule guarantees a
            value on every insert; mandatory=false at the dictionary
            level is intentional (see Constraints honored below)
          * @Column(name="cm_case_created") -> conventional ServiceNow
            column naming (lowercase snake_case `opened_date`); the
            physical column name in the underlying ServiceNow database
            is auto-generated by the platform from <element>
      - The field name is `opened_date` (lowercase, snake_case; NOT
        `created`, NOT `createdDate`, NOT `case_opened_date`) per AAP
        Section 0.5.7 verbatim. This is an INTENTIONAL rename from
        ArkCase: the source-side `created` is the audit-row creation
        timestamp (mirroring ServiceNow's auto-managed
        `sys_created_on`), whereas `opened_date` is a domain-meaningful
        synonym that captures when the case was OPENED in business
        terms - the moment a requester or internal user lodged the
        case for tracking. The two timestamps are functionally
        identical for new cases (both set at insert), but the
        domain-meaningful name better reflects the case-management
        semantic when the field appears on dashboards, reports, and
        the public portal lookup page.
      - ArkCase's `acm_case_file.cm_case_created` had `nullable=false` -
        every case in production ArkCase HAS a creation timestamp.
        AAP Section 0.5.7 carries this constraint forward as
        "Auto-set on creation", which the ServiceNow target enforces
        through the auto-set business rule + read_only=true rather
        than mandatory=true at the dictionary level.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to `x_[scope]_case`
        within the scoped application, and `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>`
        bind THIS dictionary record to the same scope by `source` attribute
        lookup. NO global-scope writes - the OOB tables `task`, `incident`,
        `sys_user`, etc. are never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical field identifier `x_[scope]_case.opened_date`
        = 3e18b5498c00dfde143bbc84fced474c) and is NOT a reference to any
        other record. The deterministic derivation makes the Update Set
        re-importable on a fresh PDI without sys_id collisions:
        re-importing the same XML on the same or any future PDI resolves
        the same sys_id and idempotently updates the same dictionary row
        rather than creating a duplicate.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP convention;
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time. The placeholder appears in `<name>`, `<sys_scope>`,
        `<sys_package>`, and `<sys_update_name>` consistently.
      - mandatory=false at the dictionary level. This is INTENTIONAL and
        critical for two reasons:
          1) The auto-set before-insert business rule
             ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml guarantees
             `opened_date = gs.nowDateTime()` on every insert that does
             not pre-populate the column. Setting mandatory=true would
             cause GlideRecord.insert() to fail with "Mandatory field
             not populated" BEFORE the business rule fires (since
             mandatory enforcement is part of the platform's pre-insert
             validation pass, executed prior to before-insert business
             rules in the standard execution order). This would block
             both the scripted REST submission endpoint
             ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
             (which does NOT explicitly set opened_date - it relies on
             the auto-set business rule) AND any internal-form-driven
             insert.
          2) The auto-set rule's "if not already set" branch allows
             synthetic seed data in
             ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml to specify
             explicit synthetic timestamps spanning the past 30 days,
             so the Manager View dashboard's "Cases opened (30 days)"
             single-score widget displays a non-zero count on a fresh
             PDI immediately after Update Set commit. mandatory=false
             at the dictionary level supports both auto-set AND
             explicit-set on the same code path without contradiction.
      - read_only=true at the dictionary level. CRITICAL SECURITY
        CONTROL: without this, an internal user (manager or agent
        editing a case through the standard form) could backdate the
        `opened_date` after the fact, distorting the
        ../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml single-score
        (AVG(closed_date - opened_date) over Closed cases) and the
        ../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml single-score
        (COUNT where opened_date >= javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(30)).
        Anonymous portal callers via
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
        also cannot tamper with this timestamp - the scripted REST
        handler whitelists only the five user-supplied input fields
        (subject, type, description, requester_name, requester_email)
        and does not pass `opened_date` from the request body. The
        before-insert business rule populates the field server-side
        on every insert path. This mirrors ArkCase's `updatable=false`
        JPA constraint (which prevented the `created` field from being
        rewritten on subsequent saves through the JPA entity manager).
        The auto-set business rule itself is exempt from the read_only
        constraint because it executes server-side on the GlideRecord
        before the validation pass - read_only governs USER-INITIATED
        writes through forms, the Table API, and import sources, not
        server-side script writes via GlideRecord.setValue().
      - default_value is EMPTY (no implicit default) per the agent
        prompt's Phase 4 verbatim. ServiceNow's static dictionary
        default_value attribute supports literal values only - a
        runtime-evaluated default like `gs.nowDateTime()` cannot be
        encoded as a static dictionary default and must instead be
        applied by the auto-set business rule. Authoring an empty
        default keeps the responsibility for population unambiguously
        in the business rule, avoiding the risk that a stale literal
        date (e.g., a historical `2025-01-01 00:00:00` baked into the
        dictionary) leaks into seed data or production cases on a
        future PDI.
      - audit=false per AAP Section 0.3.1 minimal-change clause and the
        agent prompt's Phase 4. The standard `sys_created_on` audit
        column on every ServiceNow row already captures the row's
        creation timestamp at platform-default granularity; this
        `opened_date` is a domain-meaningful copy maintained for the
        portal lookup, the dashboard reports, and the ArkCase semantic
        analog. Auditing the auto-set field redundantly with
        `sys_created_on` would duplicate audit-trail rows in the
        sys_audit table without adding investigative value, since
        read_only=true already prevents post-insert modification.
      - active=true: the field is part of the live schema from
        Update Set commit forward. There is no transitional / staged
        / inactive phase for the case schema in the POC.
      - display=true: the field renders on the standard list and form
        views for `x_[scope]_case`. Internal users (manager, agent,
        viewer) see the timestamp on the case form; the public portal
        lookup widget separately whitelists this column for its
        anonymous response.
      - max_length=40: standard ServiceNow ceiling for date/datetime
        fields. ServiceNow stores DateTime values in a canonical
        `YYYY-MM-DD HH:mm:ss` format (19 chars) with optional timezone
        offset suffix (+5 chars) - 40 chars provides ample headroom
        for any current or future canonical encoding without schema
        migration.
      - choice=0: free-form DateTime input (no choice list). The
        platform's standard date/time picker widget renders for input
        on the form; the report builder uses native DateTime
        comparison operators on the column.
      - No reference target: this is a DateTime field, not a Reference
        field. All `<reference*>` elements are empty and
        `<table_reference>false</table_reference>`.
      - text_index=false: DateTime fields are not full-text-indexed.
        The platform's standard Date/DateTime comparison operators on
        GlideRecord.addQuery() (e.g., `addQuery('opened_date',
        '>=', javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(30))`) operate directly on
        the column without needing a full-text index.
      - unique=false: cases legitimately share creation timestamps
        when bulk-imported, when seed data is loaded, or when
        independent portal submissions arrive within the same second.
        Uniqueness is enforced by the `number` field
        (CASE0000001 format, ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_number.xml),
        not by `opened_date`.
      - virtual=false: this is a stored column, not a calculated /
        virtual derivation.
      - No PII: the field stores only a UTC timestamp; no real names,
        email addresses, or organizational identifiers are derived
        from or stored in this column.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER `../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml`
        (parent table), since `<name>x_[scope]_case</name>` references
        the table by name.
      - This record MUST load BEFORE the consumers that read or write
        the `opened_date` column:
          * ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml (before-insert
            rule that populates this field with `gs.nowDateTime()` if
            not already set; the rule references the column by element
            name and would fail to compile against the table if this
            dictionary entry is absent)
          * ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml
            (returns this field as one of the three whitelisted output
            fields per AAP Section 0.7.4: "the lookup page returns ONLY
            status, subject, opened_date")
          * ../portal/widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_lookup_widget.xml
            (renders this field on the public lookup result panel)
          * ../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml (single-score:
            AVG(`closed_date - opened_date`) over Closed cases - per
            AAP Section 0.4.1 Manager View Dashboard widget inventory)
          * ../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml (single-score:
            COUNT where `opened_date >= javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(30)`
            - per AAP Section 0.4.1 Manager View Dashboard widget
            inventory)
          * ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml (synthetic
            demo cases populate this field with explicit timestamps
            spanning the past 30 days so the Manager View
            "Cases opened (30 days)" single-score displays a non-zero
            count on a fresh PDI immediately after Update Set commit;
            the auto-set business rule's "if not already set" branch
            preserves these explicit values)
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
    <sys_dictionary action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <array>false</array>
        <attributes/>
        <audit>false</audit>
        <calculation/>
        <choice>0</choice>
        <choice_field/>
        <choice_table/>
        <column_label>Opened Date</column_label>
        <comments>DateTime auto-set on case creation via ../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml. Read-only from user perspective. One of THREE fields exposed by ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml (status, subject, opened_date). Also used by ../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml and ../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml. Replaces ArkCase CaseFile.created (audit Date with @Temporal(TIMESTAMP)).</comments>
        <create_roles/>
        <default_value/>
        <defaultsort/>
        <delete_roles/>
        <dependent/>
        <dependent_on_field/>
        <display>true</display>
        <dynamic_creation>false</dynamic_creation>
        <dynamic_creation_script/>
        <dynamic_default_value/>
        <dynamic_ref_qual/>
        <element>opened_date</element>
        <element_reference>false</element_reference>
        <foreign_database/>
        <function_definition/>
        <function_field>false</function_field>
        <internal_type>glide_date_time</internal_type>
        <mandatory>false</mandatory>
        <max_length>40</max_length>
        <name>x_[scope]_case</name>
        <next_element/>
        <primary>false</primary>
        <read_only>true</read_only>
        <read_roles/>
        <reference/>
        <reference_cascade_rule/>
        <reference_floor/>
        <reference_key/>
        <reference_qual/>
        <reference_qual_condition/>
        <reference_type/>
        <sizeclass/>
        <spell_check>false</spell_check>
        <staged>false</staged>
        <sys_class_name>sys_dictionary</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>3e18b5498c00dfde143bbc84fced474c</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name/>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]_case_management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_dictionary_x_[scope]_case_opened_date</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <table_reference>false</table_reference>
        <text_index>false</text_index>
        <unique>false</unique>
        <use_dependent_field>false</use_dependent_field>
        <use_dynamic_default>false</use_dynamic_default>
        <use_reference_qualifier>simple</use_reference_qualifier>
        <virtual>false</virtual>
        <virtual_type/>
        <widget/>
        <write_roles/>
        <xml_view>false</xml_view>
    </sys_dictionary>
</record_update>
